{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{italic title}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Stay (Avon River) 983.JPG | painting_alignment = Right | image_size = 225px | title = Stay | alt = | caption = [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]] installation of ''Stay'' | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Antony Gormley]] | year = {{Start date|df=yes|2015}} | type = [[cast iron]] | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter__metric = | weight = 650 kg | diameter_imperial = | imperial_unit = ft | metric_unit = m | city = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand | coordinates = | owner = [[Christchurch City Council]] }} '''''Stay''''' are identical [[cast iron]] human form sculptures made by [[Antony Gormley]] and installed in two locations in the [[Christchurch Central City|central city]] of [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]]. The first sculpture was installed in the [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]] in September 2015. The second sculpture is still in storage at [[Canterbury Museum, Christchurch|Canterbury Museum]], to be installed in the north quadrangle of the [[Christchurch Arts Centre|Arts Centre]] in early 2016.
==Background== Gormley visited Christchurch in 2007<ref name="Press first article">{{cite news |last1=Gates |first1=Charlie |title=Antony Gormley's sculpture for Christchurch city centre revealed <!-- printed title was: "'Healing' sculptures for city revealed" --> |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/72252404/antony-gormleys-sculpture-for-christchurch-city-centre-revealed |accessdate=30 September 2015 |work=[[The Press]] |date=22 September 2015 |page=A1}}</ref> and remembers it as a city "blessed with open spaces and relatively wide streets and no great high-rises".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harper |first1=Jenny |title=A Dark and Empty Interior |url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/bulletin/168/a-dark-and-empty-interior/ |publisher=[[Christchurch Art Gallery]] |accessdate=30 September 2015 |date=31 May 2012}}</ref> The central city received massive damage in the February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]]. Gormley was approached in 2014<ref name="Gormley statue installed">{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Georgina |title=First Gormley statue put in place <!-- printed title; online title was "Gormley statue installed on the Avon River" --> |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/visual-art/72528425/gormley-statue-installed-on-the-avon-river |accessdate=30 September 2015 |work=[[The Press]] |date=30 September 2015 |page=A3}}</ref> about contributing an artwork to Christchurch, and he provided two identical cast iron sculptures that can contribute to the 'healing' of the city, as he called it.<ref name="Press first article" />
{{quote|text=Christchurch is a well-ordered city based on a 19th century urban plan which suddenly became chaotic through planetary forces rupturing human design. SCAPE 8 presents the ideal opportunity to ask whether art can instigate and give space for new attitudes and begin to heal and encourage reconciliation. Post-quake, this city is a human habitat forced by nature to reformulate. The attitude of the work I have made for it carries a sense of reflection or 'taking stock'.|author=Antony Gormley<ref>{{cite web |title=Stay |url=http://www.scapepublicart.org.nz/scape-8-antony-gormley/ |publisher=Scape Public Art |accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref>}}
Gormley stated that he made his work available at a discounted rate, and had therefore asked for the price not to be revealed.<ref name="Lynch criticism">{{cite news |last1=Lynch |first1=Chris |title=Chris Lynch: Who signed off on the sculpture? |url=http://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/opinion/chris-lynch-who-signed-off-on-the-sculpture/ |accessdate=30 September 2015 |work=[[Newstalk ZB]] |date=25 September 2015}}</ref> The purchase and installation was funded by [[Christchurch City Council]] (CCC) and the [[Canterbury Earthquake Recovery Authority]] (CERA). CCC contributed [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]502,500 towards the cost, whilst CERA would not disclose the size of their contribution.<ref name="Press first article" />
The first announcement about the legacy (i.e. permanent) artworks by Gormley was made in April 2015, when it was revealed that his work was to be installed in Christchurch as part of the Scape8 public art exhibition, to be held from 3 October to 15 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=SCAPE 8 Public Art Christchurch Biennial |url=http://www.biennialfoundation.org/2015/04/scape-8-public-art-christchurch-biennial-participating-artists-announced/ |publisher=Biennial Foundation |accessdate=30 September 2015 |date=1 April 2015}}</ref>
==Avon River installation== Avon River coordinates: {{Coord|43|31|48.43|S|172|38|0.88|E|display=inline}}
The local newspaper, ''[[The Press]]'', reported on 22 September 2015 of the pending installation of the first sculpture in the Avon River, just upstream from the Gloucester Street Bridge.<ref name="Press first article" /> A {{convert|6|m}} pile was screwed into the riverbed, and the sculpture installed onto this foundation on 29 September. This was the first work of Gormley installed in New Zealand.<ref name="Gormley statue installed" />
==Arts Centre installation== Arts Centre coordinates: {{Coord|43|31|52.58|S|172|37|41.82|E|display=inline}}
In early 2016, the second sculpture is to be installed in the north quadrangle of the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]]. As of October 2015, the main part of the Arts Centre is still under earthquake repair and not accessible to the public as yet.<ref name="Gormley statue installed" />
